In many cases these manage specific administrative functions as delegated by a government unit, such as - catchment management authorities - school zones - police and law enforcement - fire and emergency services In other cases, the administrative unit, through still formally gazetted, is primarily ceremonial or informative with few or no administrative functions, such as - city, area, rural city, borough, town, - locality - shire, parish, hundred, division For any particular function it is expected that administrative units do not intersect or overlap. There will be a relationship with the government unit that is responsible for delegating the specific function, and there may be relationships with other administrative units. Local Government Area (also referred to as local councils ):
A Local Government Area (LGA) is a geographical area under the responsibility of an incorporated local government council, or an incorporated Indigenous government council. The LGAs in Australia collectively cover only a part of Australia. The main areas not covered by LGAs are northern parts of South Australia, a large part of the Northern Territory, the western division of New South Wales, all of the Australian Capital Territory and the Other Territories. The number of LGAs and their boundaries can change over time. Their creation and delimitation is the responsibility of the respective state/territory governments, and are governed by the provisions of state/territory local government and other relevant Acts.
Areas and wards The number of electors enrolled in council areas varies from less than 1,000 to over 150,000.
Councils may be either:
- undivided - where the whole council electorate elects all the councillors for the council; or - divided into wards - where each ward electorate elects an equal number of councillors to make up the whole council.
As of November 2005 there are 152 local government areas in New South Wales. Look up a Local Government area
Ward boundary management Under section 211 of the Local Government Act 1993 councils that are divided into wards are required to keep these boundaries under review to ensure numbers of electors in each ward are approximately the same.
If a review is undertaken (which should occur once in every term in the year after an election), and a council is required to alter its ward boundaries due to a difference of greater than 10% in the number of electors between wards, the council is required to, among other things, consult the NSW Electoral Commission.
An undivided council can only divide its area into wards, or abolish wards in its area if approval is given at a referendum. All enrolled electors in a council area vote in a referendum and the result of the referendum is binding on the council.

-- Definition -- Unit of administration where a Government at some level has and/or exercises jurisdictional rights, for local, sub-national and national governance. -- Note -- In Australia this corresponds with federal, state|territory, and local government units (LGAs). There is a strict 3-level hierarchy.
The naming conventions for local governments vary across Australia. They are authorized by the state or territory government above them.
--Cities (C) --Areas (A) --Rural Cities (RC) --Boroughs (B) --Shires (S) --Towns (T) --Regional Councils (R) --Municipalities/Municipal Councils (M) --District Councils (DC) --Regional Councils (RegC) --Aboriginal Councils (AC)

The codeList corresponds to a register of adminstrative unit types, where the register is indicated by the dictionary identifier (tagged value). The AdministrativeUnit_TypeTerm is a specialization of the TypeTerm from the Core Definition Model. The values include: -Named areas without any other functional significance --Suburb --Locality --City --Parish --Region --Hundred (SA) --Division (ACT) -Units defined for the purposes of some adminstrative function or service provided on behalf of government --Primary school zone --Secondary school zone --Fire and emergency service area --Police district --Health district --Catchment management authority -

-- Definition -- Generic administrative unit feature type. -- Note -- This covers administrative unit types that are not modeled in a more specialized schema.
In many cases these relate to a specific administrative or service function, as delegated by the relevant government unit. These include - catchment management authorities - school zones - police districts - fire and emergency service areas - cadastral units (county, district, parish, hundred, division)
In other cases, the unit, through formally gazetted, is primarily ceremonial or informative with few or no administrative functions, such as - city, metropolitan area - locality, suburb
Administrative units generally do not intersect or overlap for a particular function or service within the scope of the government unit that authorizes it.
There is a relationship with the government unit that is responsible for delegating the specific function, and there may be relationships with other administrative units.

-- Definition -- This class is an indicative placeholder only for a vocabulary of terms describing the type of local government unit. Users are encouraged to use the vocabulary of unit types provided by the FSDF vocabularies working group.
-- Description --
The naming conventions for local governments vary across Australia. They can be called cities, shires, towns, or municipalities, but they are still controlled by the state or territory government above them. The types of LGAs in each state and the Northern Territory are:

Cities (C) Areas (A) Rural Cities (RC) Boroughs (B) Shires (S) Towns (T) Regional Councils (R) Municipalities/Municipal Councils (M) District Councils (DC) Regional Councils (RegC) Aboriginal Councils (AC)
